  "prompt": "How do QR codes work?",
  "response": "QR codes (Quick Response codes) are two-dimensional barcodes that can store information, such as URLs, text, or other data, in a format that can be scanned and interpreted by QR code readers or smartphones with camera capabilities. Here's a breakdown of how they work:\n\n### Structure of a QR Code\n1. **Modules**: A QR code is made up of black and white squares called modules. The arrangement of these squares encodes the data.\n2. **Finder Patterns**: Located at three corners of the code, these square patterns enable scanners to recognize the QR code's orientation and size.\n3. **Timing Patterns**: These alternating dark and light modules help the scanner determine the density of the data.\n4. **Version Information**: This part indicates the version of the QR code being used, which determines the size and data capacity.\n5. **Data and Error Correction**: The core component of the QR code, which contains the encoded information and the error correction codes that allow the QR code to be read even if it's partially damaged or obscured.\n\n### Data Encoding\n- **Data Capacity**: QR codes can store varying amounts of data depending on their version and error correction level. They can hold numbers, alphanumeric characters, binary, and kanji characters.\n- **Error Correction**: QR codes use error correction techniques (based on Reed-Solomon codes) that allow them to be readable even if they are partially damaged. Different levels of error correction (L, M, Q, H) can be chosen based on the environment where the code will be used.\n\n### Scanning Process\n1. **Capture**: A QR code scanner (usually a smartphone camera or dedicated QR code reader) captures an image of the QR code.\n2. **Decoding**: The scanner software identifies the finder patterns to determine the QR code's orientation and then analyzes the arrangement of black and white modules.\n3. **Data Extraction**: The software decodes the binary data stored in the patterns and converts it back into human-readable information such as a text message, URL, or contact information.\n\n### Applications\n- **Marketing**: QR codes enable quick access to promotional websites, discounts, or product information.\n- **Payments**: Used in mobile payment systems to facilitate transactions.\n- **Event Check-ins**: QR codes can streamline the check-in process at events or venues.\n- **Product Tracking**: Used in logistics to track inventory and shipping.\n\nOverall, QR codes are versatile tools that leverage simple visual patterns to convey a wealth of information efficiently and effectively.",
